Operational System: Bank

A bank is an example of an operational system.

Variability: Customers arrive at different times and need different services, such as deposits, withdrawals, or loans.

Complexity: A bank has many parts, including customers, employees, service counters, and computer systems.

Interconnectedness: All parts of the bank work together. Employees use computer systems to serve customers, and problems in one part can affect the whole system.

Therefore, a bank is a good example of a system that has variability, complexity, and interconnectedness.
